@NODE "Mail_20" "A question of size"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Thu, 30 Sep 1999 06:14:33 -0500
Subject: A question of size
X-UIDL: 058e3be2ff2e9f3bb6d833f981292a72
Status: U

--BOUNDARY.1748222888.1

Hi Everybody,

I need to resize a picture, which is in a chunky buffer, to another chunky.

I am using the attached routine.  Does anybody have a better way?
By better, I mean faster - the attached routine does work perfectly, but
it's rather slow because of the multiplication needed for each pixel.  I
think it would be faster with some LSL's or something, but I don't know how
to do those except for simple multiply * 2 and such...

Any ideas?

BTW, the NCpoint and NCplot work the same as the regular Point and Plot
commands, only on the chunky buffers...

Later...
-- 
I will see it when I believe it.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/


--BOUNDARY.1748222888.1
Content-Disposition: attachment; filename="ReScale.asc"

offsetX.q=CurrentWidth/NewWidth
  offsetY.q=CurrentHeight/NewHeight

  For y.w=0 To NewHeight-1              ;for each new pixel position
    For x.w=0 To NewWidth-1             ;find the right location
      xplace.w=x*offsetX
      yplace.w=y*offsetY
      pixel.b=NCPoint(1,xplace,yplace)  ;in the current chunky
      NCPlot 2,x,y,pixel                ;and transfer to the new
    Next x
  Next y


--BOUNDARY.1748222888.1

