From: Sami =?iso-8859-1?Q?N=E4=E4t=E4nen?= <sami.naatanen@dlc.fi>
Date: Thu, 30 Sep 1999 20:12:07 +0300
Subject: Re: A question of size
X-UIDL: af8278f510a87f2b5c1a83047c15bf2b
Status: U

--BOUNDARY.1717769832.1
Encoding: quoted-printable

On 30-Sep-99, Curt Esser wrote.

> Hi Everybody,
> =

> I need to resize a picture, which is in a chunky buffer, to another
> chunky.
> =

> I am using the attached routine. Does anybody have a better way? By
> better, I mean faster - the attached routine does work perfectly, but i=
t's
> rather slow because of the multiplication needed for each pixel. I thin=
k
> it would be faster with some LSL's or something, but I don't know how t=
o
> do those except for simple multiply * 2 and such...
> =

> Any ideas?
> =

> BTW, the NCpoint and NCplot work the same as the regular Point and Plot=

> commands, only on the chunky buffers...
> =

> Later...

So here it is modified and should be a lot faster.

-- =


       Sami N=E4=E4t=E4nen
       EMail: sami.naatanen@dlc.fi


--BOUNDARY.1717769832.1
Content-Disposition: attachment; filename="ReScale.asc"
Content-Description: Optimized rescale code

offsetX.q=CurrentWidth/NewWidth
offsetY.q=CurrentHeight/NewHeight
yplace.q=0
For y.w=0 To NewHeight-1              ;for each new pixel position
  xplace.q=0
  For x.w=0 To NewWidth-1             ;find the right location
    xplace.q+offsetX
    pixel.b=NCPoint(1,xplace,yplace)  ;in the current chunky
    NCPlot 2,x,y,pixel                ;and transfer to the new
  Next x
  yplace.q+offsetY
Next y


--BOUNDARY.1717769832.1

