Hi all,

I've just converted this piece of code, which supposedly shows the
current phase of the moon...

I can't see it at the moment, so could someone who can see the moon
try it out? :)

According to the original source, it worked very well in Southern
California, but since we're all on the same side of the moon, it
should work equally well anywhere - assuming the moon's in view of
course ;)

If it does work, I'll be adding a visual representation of course...

See ya,
-- 
<tsb>
<sb>James L Boyd - jamesboyd@all-hail.freeserve.co.uk
<sb>Member of Team *AMIGA*, and *Dogbert's New Ruling Class.*
<sb>Connected from Dundee, Scotland. 
<sb>(http://surf.to/all-hail/)
<tsb>

But what is all this fear of and opposition to oblivion? What
is the matter with the soft darkness, the dreamless sleep?
-- James Thurber

--BOUNDARY.1748386144.1
Content-Disposition: attachment; filename="MoonPhases.asc"
Encoding: quoted-printable
Content-Description: Shows phase of the moon

=2E
=2ENotesByJLB

; Original BSD Unix code circa 1980.
; ANSI-C modified by Lynn Nash.
; Algorithm by Martin Minow.
; Blitzed-up by James L Boyd.
=2E
=2EOriginal

; Notes from ANSI-C Source...

; Output the phase of the moon for the given year, month, day.

; The routine calculates the year's epact (the age of the moon on
; Jan 1.), adds this to the number of days in the year, and
; calculates the phase of the moon for this date.

; In the algorithm:

;  diy    Is the day of the year - 1 (i.e., Jan 1 is day 0).

;  golden Is the number of the year in the Mentonic Cycle,
;         used to determine the position of the calender moon.

;  epact  Is the age of the calender moon (in days) at the
;         beginning of the year.  to calculate epact, two
;         century-based corrections are applied:

;           Gregorian:      (3 * cent)/4 - 12
;                   is the number of Years such as 1700, 1800
;                   when leap year was NOT held.

;           Clavian:        (((8 * cent) + 5) / 25) - 5
;                   is a correction to the Mentonic Cycle of
;                   about 8 days evry 2500 Years.  Note that
;                   this will overflow 16 bits in the year
;                   409600.  Beware.

; The algorithm is accurate for the Gregorian calender only.

; The magic numbers used in the phase calculation are as follows:

;     29.5    The moon's period in days.
;    177      29.5 scaled by 6
;     22      (29.5 / 8) scaled by 6 (this gets the phase)
;     11      ((29.5 / 8) / 2) scaled by 6

; Theoretically, this should yield a number in the range 0 .. 7.
; However, two days per year, things don't work out too well.

; Here we go :)
=2E
=2EMoonPhase

Function.b MoonPhase {day.b,month.b,year.w}

; I have NO IDEA WHATSOEVER what this stuff does :)

  Dim day.w (13)
  Restore dayz:For a=3D1 To 13:Read day(a):Next a

  dayz:
  Data.w -1,-1,30,58,89,119,150,180,211,241,272,303,333

  DEFTYPE.b phase  ; Moon's phase
  DEFTYPE.b cent   ; Century number (1979 =3D 20)
  DEFTYPE.l epact  ; Age of the moon on Jan. 1
  DEFTYPE.l diy    ; Day in the year
  DEFTYPE.l golden ; Moon's golden number

  If month<0 OR month>12 Then month=3D0 ; Just in case
  diy=3Dday+day(month)                  ; Day in the year

  If ((month>2) AND ((year MOD 4=3D0) AND ((year MOD 400=3D0) OR (year MO=
D 100<>0)))) Then diy+1 ; leap year fix

  cent   =3D (year/100)+1       ;           Century number
  golden =3D (year MOD 19)+1    ;           Golden number

  epact  =3D ((11*golden)+20+(((8*cent)+5)/25)-5-(((3*cent)/4)-12)) MOD 3=
0

  If epact<=3D0 Then epact+30 ; Age range is 1 .. 30
  If (epact=3D25 AND golden>11) OR epact=3D24 Then epact+1

   ; Calculate the phase, using the magic numbers defined above.
   ; Note that (phase AND 7) is equivalent To (phase MOD 8) AND
   ; is needed On two Days per year (when the algorithm yields 8).

  phase =3D (((((diy+epact)*6)+11) MOD 177)/22) AND 7

  Function Return phase

End Function
=2E
=2EDemo

d$=3DDate$(SystemDate)

d.b=3DVal(Left$(d$,2))
m.b=3DVal(Mid$ (d$,4,2))  ; Days, Months, Years aren't working here!!!
y.w=3DVal(Mid$ (d$,7,4))  ; Anyone guess why?!

; Note return values 0 - 7 and their meanings :

Select MoonPhase {d,m,y}
  Case 0
    phase$=3D"new"
  Case 1
    phase$=3D"waxing crescent"
  Case 2
    phase$=3D"in its first quarter"
  Case 3
    phase$=3D"waxing gibbous"
  Case 4
    phase$=3D"full"
  Case 5
    phase$=3D"waning gibbous"
  Case 6
    phase$=3D"in its last quarter"
  Case 7
    phase$=3D"waning crescent"
End Select

PutStr_ "MoonPhaser : The moon is "+phase$+"."+Chr$(10)
PutStr_                                        Chr$(10)
PutStr_ "(Date : "+d$+")"                     +Chr$(10)

=2E
=2EENABLE

; MouseWait ; ENABLE while developing!

End

--BOUNDARY.1748386144.1--




