@NODE "Mail_80" "Re: ASM strings (was Freeing bsdsocket.library)"
From: "David McMinn" <dave@satanicdreams.com>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Mon, 4 Oct 1999 10:56:18 +0100
Subject: Re: ASM strings (was Freeing bsdsocket.library)
Encoding: 8bit
X-UIDL: 5bd2c0a2e5089b867c9d8b7d18fc2ff5

Hi Rick

> I started work on a proper Blitz library for TCP/IP a few months ago,
> but I sort of drifted off it because there was a problem with
> returning strings back to the main program.  The developer docs for
> Blitz libraries don't mention returning strings, just getting them
> from the stack.  If anybody can supply some info on this, I'll happily
> continue makin the library.

Funny enough, I done this stuff about a month ago. Just had to get 
the ways of doing it from other libraries source, and I thought I'd 
cracked it, but who knows, since there ain't no guidelines. Anyhoo, 
this is what I've got:

Pointer to the string is passed in the data register, as other 
parameters are

The length of each string is stored on the stack (longwords), but a2 
is preloaded to point to the start of the strings, so you can use
-4(a2) to get the length of the first string, -8(a2) for the second 
and so on.

When returning a string, you just stick the characters into (a3)+, as 
commands that return a string get a3 pre-loaded with a pointer to the 
string buffer (or part of it). When the command returns, a3 should 
point to the NULL character. The length of the string should be 
returned in d0 (not including NULL).

There are also a couple of routines, for allocating (and copying) a 
new string and freeing a string. I can't remember the parameters for 
these, or the token numbers, but you use ALibJSR. I'll send you the 
details for these once I get home.


-- 
|) /\ \/ ][ |)   |\/| © |\/| ][ |\| |\|   |   dave@satanicdreams.com
   http://members.xoom.com/David_McMinn   |   ICQ=16827694
Consciousness: That annoying time between naps.

