@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_99" "Re: Blitting"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Wed, 01 Sep 1999 18:10:56 -0500
Subject: Re: Blitting
X-UIDL: 5c7c2eea794e45763eb70065d919d01c

Hi Vic

On 01-Sep-99, Vic E Babes wrote:
> Hello, ppl
> 
> Can anyone explain to me how to use the extended BBlit command that
> instructs the blitter which bitplanes to `miss out` for shapes that don`t
> use the full palette - I can`t tell if I`m getting them the right way
> around - the manual is less than useful.
> 
> If, for example, I have a 32 colour palette, but have some shapes that
> only use the first 16 colours, what format would the BBlit command take to
> ensure that the processor doesn`t bother with the second 16 colours.

The "Excess ON/OFF" parameter for blitting goes like this:

Bit one is the first EXCESS bitplane - (in your example it would actually be
the Third actual bitplane), the next bit - the next bitplane, etc.

So, "Blit Shape#, X, Y, %11"  should do the job - or maybe  %00 - I don't
remember exactly which way is correct - try 'em both and see.

Or just use %11111111  (or %00000000) to turn on/off any possible number of
excess bitplanes...

Later...
-- 
The man who can smile when things go
wrong has thought of someone to blame it on.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/



