@NODE "Mail_154" "Re: color 0"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Wed, 13 Oct 1999 07:12:32 -0500
Subject: Re: color 0
X-UIDL: d17d0004a85db8007b98b3c10fce2d69

Hi Emil

On 10-Oct-99, Emil Oppeln Bronikowski wrote:
> Yello,
> 
> well, could somebody could give me a hint?
> 
> i have open window and blitted a big shape on it, next i adding some gt
> buttons, and gtshapes... why gtshapes not using color zero to be
> transparent? 

I think this is because GadTools treats the gadgets as images rather than as
shapes.  So it shows the whole thing.

There are a couple of solutions I can think of:

1 (if you are always using the same picture for the window "background")

Load the background picture in your paint program, and paste the gadget
images on it where you want them to be.  Now grab the gadget "shapes" from
this, with the background included and use these for your shape-gadgets


2 (if the background pic will not always be the same)

- load in the pic to the window
- use GetAShape to grab the exact location where the gadget will be
- use ShapesBitMap on this shape, so you can draw on it.
- now load the gadget shape into another shape, and blit it onto the first
shape
- now you can use the first shape for the shapegadget

If this doesn't make sense, let me know and I will make a little example.

Later...
-- 

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




