--BOUNDARY.272979512.1

Hello Rick

> Attached is the altered library. But please note that if you use this, any
> program that used the List.mui and Listview.mui will now automatically use
> the NList classes instead. But please don't ask me for help, the library
> still belongs to Erwan Fouret and Andreas Hakansson...I just tweaked it a
> bit :)

The only problem with this is the fact that the List commands in the
EFMUILib are crap, and you cant dynamically change an inserted entry.
Not to mention all the damn bugs with Multi column lists... There are TONNES
or them.

I wonder if Andreas Hakansson can fix these bugs and add NList support
properly? That would be good. Infact it would be VERY GOOD!.. I dont know
enough about list
I dont think Erwan Fouret programs in blitz or maybe not even for the
amiga anymore?

Anyway, another EFMUILib.obj is attached to this email, it has sperate
commands for handling NLists..

   - MUINList()
   - MUINListView()
   - MUINListHook On|Off

The other commands should work directly with NLists. (MUIListInsert, etc..)

I haven`t tested it properly, so again, dont complain, but it seems to be
working with the EFMultiList example (also attached.)

Oh the modified source is there too ;)

I might have missed something in the lib, I haven`t tested it with NLists
and normal lists in the same application. So I dont know.

The worse thing is the fact that you cant use the #MUIM_NList_ReplaceSingle
command with this because the memory for each entry in the list
is a variable string, and you end up over-running the memory area.
My suggestion (if you want to dynamically alter things in the list) is to
open your own memory when inserting into the list.. Hold the memory
locations in an array until the list is cleared then free them (IE a custom
Construct and Destruct Hook) This is actually what the EFMUILib does,
it only sets a Display hook IFAICT.

-- 

Rob,
