@NODE "Mail_200" "Re: Dithering"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Tue, 12 Oct 1999 18:43:45 +0100
From: "Vic E Babes" <zalda@home4968.freeserve.co.uk>
Subject: Re: Dithering
Date: Tue, 12 Oct 1999 18:41:36 +0100
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit
X-UIDL: 45aece2e6a761043a854064bcb2b5177

INTERACTIVE COMPUTER GRAPHICS
Functional, Procedural and Device Level Methods
Peter Burger/Duncan Gillies

ISBN 0-201-17439-1

First printed in 1989.
Published by Addison-Wesley

Algorithms are written in PASCAL, which is very similar to Blitz Basic
in Syntax, but PLOT for example, is SET_PIXEL in PASCAL.

Although I would be quite happy to type the relevant sections out (I'm
a touch-typist), I'm worried about infringing copyright laws.  I've
read the relevant section, but only have a basic understanding of how
it works - trouble is that it refers to earlier sections and functions
on half-toning, and then continues onto algorithms for error-correction
algorithms to avoid 'streaks' - where Floyd-Steinberg come in.

However, if you've used the image processing tools in various art packages
such as PPaint, etc, you will no doubt have seen the matrices that they
use:

 0000  0000  0000  0000
 0000  00x0  0xx0  00x0
 0x00  0x00  0x00  0xx0
 0000  0000  0000  0000

Basically, you look at a part of the picture, and decide what the intensity
is, and then alter the colours accordingly with the above matrices.  The
book only goes into 2-colour dithering, as it states that "...it is very
difficult to develop a comprehensive and scientific method for dithering
in general, and the difficulties are much more severe when colour is used."
And it also states that most printers can print in 8 colours, so it seems
out of date on those grounds - though it does go into ray-tracing later,
so the book does deal with colour, and a lot of basic algorithms haven't
changed over the last 10 years.

I've only used it for one of the elipse algorithms, and I had to write my
own error-correction routine for that, as it tends to leave 'L' shaped
pixels - much like Icon-Edit does on the edges of the elipses, instead of
'\' shaped.

The book itself Contains:

FUNDAMENTAL ALGORITHMS FOR RASTER GRAPHICS
  Line Drawing
  Polygon Filling
  Conic Section Generation
  Anti-aliasing
  Generation of Pictures on Bi-level Devices

ANALYSIS OF TWO AND THREE DIMENSIONAL SPACE
  Vectors and Cartesian Space
  Vector Line Equation
