Hi Chris

On 14-Oct-99, Chris Deeney wrote:
> Hi guys! :)
> 
> I know how to execute a program fairly easyly from within blitz using:-
> 
> cmd$="Run >NIL: prog"
> e=Execute_(&cmd,0,0)
> 
> This works fine, but how do i get the program to display it's ouput
> as normal through it's 'Output Window' without crashing with a msg
> in the window saying something like "Cli [9]" ? any ideas?

If the program opens it's own output window, it shouldn't be a problem.

I suppose you are trying to run a CLI-only command, which needs the Shell's
window for it's output?
Here is one way.

I'm sure there are more glamourous methods using the input and output file
parameters, but this one works OK here...

Notice that it automatically "detaches" itself - no need to use "RUN" in the
Execute_ string.

I have shown this in the demo by having it print some nonsense into it's own
window before and after running the command.

The main program will shut it's own window and end after a bit, but the
output window will stick around until you close it yourself.

Later...
-- 
Everyone has a photographic memory.  Some don't have film.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/


--BOUNDARY.1748618552.1
Content-Disposition: attachment; filename="ExecuteToWindow.asc"

WBStartup
NoCli
WBenchToFront_
WbToScreen 0

Window 0,0,0,250,50,0,"Test Window",-1,-1      ;our program's window

NPrint "Ready!"
VWait 200

win$="> CON:0/50///Our_Output/CLOSE/WAIT"      ;the command's output window

ex$="C:version "+win$+" C:setpatch"

dummy=Execute_(&ex$,0,0)

NPrint "Command executed "
VWait 200
NPrint "I'm closing soon"
VWait 200

End


--BOUNDARY.1748618552.1--




@ENDNODE
