@NODE "Mail_266" "Re: Freeing bsdsocket.library"
From: "David McMinn" <dave@satanicdreams.com>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Thu, 30 Sep 1999 18:33:09 +0100
Subject: Re: Freeing bsdsocket.library
Encoding: 8bit
X-UIDL: b26074d43446e29cbdb6c0b165f33b6d
Status: U

> When my program starts, it automatically tries to open all of the
> libraries that it needs. This is, I guess, the way that Blitz handles
> libraries because I have nothing to do with it ;) One of these

Yep, and its one of the many "features" of Blitz.

> libraries is bsdsocket.library, which is only present if
> Miami/Genesis/AmiTCP etc. are running. The trouble is, if I then try
> and quit Miami (in my case) then it complains my program is still
> using it's libraries and won't release them.

Doesn't it always do that though, i.e. if you quit Miami before 
Voyager it moans about it. I know it definately does it with 
FTPHandler. Thats what pisses me off about these programs, they won't 
use the library only when needed, like YAM or Netscape. They'll let 
you sit there and play around until you do something that needs an 
internet connection and then try to use the library. Much nicer.

> Has anybody any idea how I can get around this?

Well, if you're up to it, you could recode all your routines which 
call a bsdsocket.library function to use ASM. That way, Blitz won't 
open the library automatically, and its up to you. If you're using 
Paul Burkey's TCP functions, then it won't be so bad, because you'll 
only need to convert the code to ASM once. Even if you're not using 
those functions, it may be worthwhile making dummy functions, all 
that they do is call the real bsdsocket.library function, but use ASM.

You could also try finding out where Blitz keeps the pointer to the 
bsdsocket.library (it'll be a negative offset from register a5). *If* 
you find that out, close the library (using that pointer), and set 
the pointer to zero. Now you do all the opening and closing of the 
library, but just store/clear the pointer in the offset you found. 
Definately open it before you use the functions. Or at least make 
sure that it is open. The offset will be proportional to the library 
number of the bsdsocket.library and how many of the libraries with 
higher numbers you are using. And probably the object and string 
buffer sizes.

I think the second method is best described using a well known phrase 
which contains the words "haystack" and "needle" :)


-- 
|) /\ \/ ][ |)   |\/| © |\/| ][ |\| |\|   |   dave@satanicdreams.com
   http://members.xoom.com/David_McMinn   |   ICQ=16827694
