@NODE "Mail_269" "Re: Freeing bsdsocket.library"
From: "David McMinn" <dave@satanicdreams.com>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Fri, 1 Oct 1999 09:55:10 +0100
Subject: Re: Freeing bsdsocket.library
Encoding: 8bit
X-UIDL: 677246a883b59cbd744f454026aa6bed

> I am using Paul Burkey's TCP functions, but have *no* idea how to
> rewrite them using ASM. Is there any place I can go to find out about
> this?

Actually, you can do it with a minimum amount of ASM. It'll be pretty 
ugly though.

You'll need a copy of the bsdsocket.fd file, which should come with 
Miami or AmiTCP etc, so you can get the offsets for the commands and 
the registers that the parameters go in.

You'll need to control the opening and closing of the library 
yourself, using OpenLibrary_ and CloseLibrary_ and storing the 
library base in a long variable.

When you come to need to rewrite a function call, you'll need to do a 
couple of things:

Find out the offset for the library function (from .fd file)
Find out what registers parameters are passed in (from .fd file)

Now, rewrite the library function call e.g.

blah=GetHostByName_(hostname$)

converts to something like:

GetReg a6,bsdlibbase  ; Put library pointer into a6
GetReg a0,&hostname$  ; Set up parameters into correct registers
                      ; Do any other parameters in here
JSR    -60(a6)        ; Call the library function (-60 is the offset)
PutReg d0,blah        ; Store result of function call

And of course, you'd need to put the checks to make sure 
bsdsocket.library was open in the correct places in your code.


-- 
|) /\ \/ ][ |)   |\/| © |\/| ][ |\| |\|   |   dave@satanicdreams.com
   http://members.xoom.com/David_McMinn   |   ICQ=16827694
