@NODE "Mail_277" "Re: Freeing bsdsocket.library"
Date: Mon, 04 Oct 1999 03:35:26 +0100
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
X-Accept-Language: en
Subject: Re: Freeing bsdsocket.library
Encoding: 7bit
X-UIDL: d7b13716e02ff6ed9cd8e1500d1587e2

Roger Light wrote:
> On 03-Oct-99, Paul Burkey wrote:
> > Roger Light wrote:
> >> I'm going to convert TCPFuncs completely if that's OK with Paul...
> > Sure, feel free to copy/use/rewrite and redistribute the TCPFuncs
> > code however you wish.
> 
> Excellent, cheers ;) I'll just tidy it all up a bit and post them to the
> list.
> 
> > The new game is actually coded in C++, So I never really managed to
> > utilize those functions after all!
> 
> Heh, never mind. They've been useful to lots of people I imagine ;)

They were designed to be used 'as is' but also as a demo of how the
bsdsocket.library can be tamed to become fairly simple to use.

> How far into writing your new game are you?

Thats hard to say because there's no real way of measuring such
a project. I've only been working on it for the past 2-3 months
but I've written over 480k of C++ source code so far.  The original
Blitz Foundation sources were 590k so I guess I've got the bulk of
the recoding done so far. I was going to use a Blitz->C conversion
batch process to do most of the work but I realized that is was
better to do it all by hand since there's a lot of important
restructuring to be made, especially by taking advantage of C++
OOP functionality. Still, there's more to the new game than just
rewriting it in a different language. The release date was extended
into the first half of 2000 which will probably turn out to be
WoA2000; quite a nice release date since it was only WoA99 when
the project was first conceived.

Cheers,

Paul

-- 
< Paul Burkey http://www.sneech.freeserve.co.uk >

