@NODE "Mail_324" "Re: GTText gadgets"
Date: Tue, 14 Sep 1999 02:40:25 +0200
From: Mikkel =?iso-8859-1?Q?L=F8kke?= <FlameDuck@software.dk>
Subject: Re: GTText gadgets
X-UIDL: 254886b55cd827bf84d4998988b2671c

At 05:44 10-09-99 -0500, you wrote:

>First of all, does anybody know how to make YAM display the character "#"
>all the time, rather than changing the text colours?
>
>Anyway, if you are using YAM, please save this letter as Plain text first
>and read it with a text reader, or the code below will not be shown
>correctly...
>
>Does this happen with other email programs too?

Here's the thing. Sometime in the eighties (AFAIR), on bulletin boards and
esp. on FIDOnet a great standard was born (It all started on UNIX systems
then I'm not quite sure where it came from before FIDO, but people have
suggested UNIX). The Idea was that you could change the type of the text
printed by enclosing your words in special charecters, *, _, /, which would
set the text of the word to *Bold*, _Underlined_, and /Italics/. (The
#Colour# thing wqas added much later) Problem is YAM  doesn't interpret
them correctly, try loading them in SPOT or Thor (the mails) and they
should turn out right.


/FlameDuck/


