@NODE "Mail_492" "Re: Naslrequest"
Sender: tdc98@doc.ic.ac.uk
Date: Tue, 05 Oct 1999 13:08:03 +0100
From: Thomas Cobb <tdc98@doc.ic.ac.uk>
X-Accept-Language: en
Subject: Re: Naslrequest
Encoding: 7bit
X-UIDL: 90ab67371b1c491bf8517382847ee035

amorel wrote:

> On 04-Oct-99, Thomas Cobb wrote:
>
> C=functions that take a string as an argument what you actually pass is a
> C=pointer to a string.
>
> Well, I find that silly =) Anyway, it works now thanks. Btw, why is there
> a & before the variable, I thought a * shows a pointer. Or can one use
> both?

A pointer is a variable which holds an address, and when you pass it to the
function you are basically giving the function the address of a string.  The &
means "address of" so &var$ is the address of var$.  It just saves you having
to define a pointer.

    Thom



