X-UIDL: 49e1cd7aeec54483b5209870a526f4cd

Hi amorel

On 04-Oct-99, amorel wrote:

> 
> C=functions that take a string as an argument what you actually pass is a
> C=pointer to a string. 
> 
> Well, I find that silly =) Anyway, it works now thanks.

You must remember that Blitz is really not a true "Basic" language - it is
actually a cross between "C" and "Basic"  (and ASM, for that matter)

If you want to do things the "Basic" way, then just use the standard
ASLFileRequest$ command.

To use the more advanced "C" like stuff, you must do things the "C" way,
with pointers and structures... 


> Btw, why is there
> a & before the variable, I thought a * shows a pointer. Or can one use
> both?

& means the address (in memory) of the variable.

So, "& mystring$"  gives the address of mystring$ so OS functions can find
it.

"*mystring" would instead set up a new variable named *mystring, just as
"mystring.b" would set up a byte variable.  

It would actually point to nothing, until you specify what it points to.

So yes, both are pointers, but they are used in different ways.

Later...
-- 

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/



