@NODE "Mail_542" "Oddity"
From: "Tony Rolfe" <edgewater@shoalhaven.net.au>
Organization: Edgewater Motel, Burrill Lake, NSW 2539 Australia
Date: 9 Oct 99 13:16:02 +1000
Subject: Oddity
Encoding: 7bit
X-UIDL: 2ad48ebed2941537691173da60303b0a

I've just debugged a wierd thing.

The construct:

If some test
    do something
else
    do something else
else
    do something useless
endif

Actually compiles correctly!

Given about 100 lines of code between the two elses, it took me ages
to work out!!

Just thought that might help/amuse someone.

Cheers

-- 
Tony Rolfe
Amiga 2000, 68030/25, 1+8Mb
www.shoalhaven.net.au/edgewater


@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_543" "Re: Oddity"
From: Sami =?iso-8859-1?Q?N=E4=E4t=E4nen?= <sami.naatanen@dlc.fi>
Date: Sat, 09 Oct 1999 10:07:09 +0300
Subject: Re: Oddity
Encoding: 8bit
X-UIDL: 97f8ed6f2ddcf3ddced04efc2b3f33e8

On 09-Oct-99, Tony Rolfe wrote.

> I've just debugged a wierd thing.
> 
> The construct:
> 
> If some test
>    do something
> else
>    do something else
> else
>    do something useless
> endif
> 
> Actually compiles correctly!
> 
> Given about 100 lines of code between the two elses, it took me ages
> to work out!!
> 
> Just thought that might help/amuse someone.
> 
> Cheers
>

Well that's quite odd yes, but it works.

but the functionality of else in blitz is made so that you can use else
just to togle the if-else state.

so this is perfectly legal too!!!!!

If test
>    do if test true
> else
>    do if test false
> else
>    do if test true
> else
>    do if test false
> else
>    do if test true
> else
>    do if test false
> else
>    do if test true
> else
>    do if test false
> else
>    do if test true
> else
>    do if test false
> else
>    do if test true
> else
>    do if test false
> else
>    do if test true
> else
>    do if test false
> else
>    do if test true
> else
>    do if test false
> endif

But is quite hard to follow, isn't it. :)

-- 

       Sami Näätänen
       EMail: sami.naatanen@dlc.fi




@ENDNODE
