@NODE "Mail_565" "Palette question..."
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Mon, 25 Oct 1999 20:40:50 -0500
Subject: Palette question...
X-UIDL: 8be0cd7221fe7f1eb8b74c8d4c726cff

Hi All,

OK, first read this bit of text from the RKM's:


    Previously, under ECS, palette data was stored as 4-bit RGB
    components each left justified in a byte.  These should now be stored
    as a full 8-bit RGB values by duplicating 4-bit values in the high
    and low nibble of the byte.

Huh???  How the heck do I do this?  OK, under AGA, the palette data is
already 8 bits - no problem.

But, on an ECS machine, if I read the palette data, I'll get a 4bit result
of only 0-15, right?

So, the question is, how do I duplicate it into the high and low nibble?

Thanx...
-- 

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_566" "Re: Palette question..."
    26 Oct 99 10:13:34 +0100
From: "David McMinn" <D.Mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Tue, 26 Oct 1999 10:13:30 +0100
Subject: Re: Palette question...
Encoding: 8bit
X-UIDL: 2e36cf614c588cd905117192af10c8e8

Hi Curt

> OK, first read this bit of text from the RKM's:

Ahh, standard RKM random gibberish.

> Huh???  How the heck do I do this?  OK, under AGA, the palette data is
> already 8 bits - no problem.

Yep, on AGA, say a value which was 8 bits long: xxxxxxxx
on ECS you'd have a nibble:                         xxxx

You're trying to left justify the bits, so that the most significant 
bits (leftmost) are aligned, so you want them to look like this:

AGA: xxxxxxxx 00000000 00000000 00000000
ECS: xxxx0000 00000000 00000000 00000000

So for both, left shift the number 24 times, and if it is an ECS 
machine, do an extra 4 left shifts.


-- 
