@NODE "Mail_577" "Phoenix, etc."
From: Donovan Reeve <bubby.lnk@ispi.net>
Date: Sat, 16 Oct 1999 08:11:47 +0500
Subject: Phoenix, etc.
Encoding: 8bit
X-UIDL: 2a444947c39cc5879254683cad22c415

On 16-Oct-99, Mikkel Lřkke flashed:
>At 13:40 15-10-99 +0500, you wrote:

>>>Wow, aint that spiffy.... not ;-)
>>>That phoenix stuff is again an attempt at baking air :-)

>>  Well, I thought that at first too, and it still remains to be seen.
>>But with all the Amiga-knowledgeable people getting involved, they may
>>have a chance to do something worthwhile.  Hmmm... We shall see.

>I don't get it, what is it with AMiGA mentality ? Have we really reached a
>level of self pity where we sit arround sobbing that no-one likes us
>anymore ? Let's take iWin, they've had a rough time by any measures, what's


-Clip-


>Then there's Phoenix, KOSH, UGN and everyone else trying to make a
>difference, but no, why should we support them, I mean Phoneix is
>unquestionably AMiGA, everyone that was at San Jose, who built the original
>A1000, and who is still alive, is supporting it, why the hell can't we ?

-Clip-


  Well, that's about what I really meant to say, but I was trying to be
tactfull and keep it short.   ;)

  I actually feel that some of these things have a good chance of
succeeding, and as you say, what have we got to lose by being supportive?

  I still have a Boxer on order (since June of 1998) and am looking forward
to finelly recieving it about the end of this year.  I know it isn't next
generation, but it will be powerfull and modern enough to fill my needs for
the time, and will power my software sufficiently to make it a pleasure to
use.  I will of course put a G4 accellerator in it almost right away.

  Actually, for all those willing to upgrade their hardware with a PPC
accelerator, a fast hard drive, a decent amount of ram, Amiga OS3.5,
and a graphics card the Amiga suffers no handicap compared to present
machinery of other platforms.  The cost to do that is nearly as much as
buying a wintel but so what, it's what you end up with for the money that
counts.  I use both wintel and Mac at work, mainly for art and DTP.
The Amiga fares better than the wintels for both areas of work, and better
than the Macs for painting.  Amiga is comparable to Mac for DTP, being
better in some ways, not as good in a few.  Amiga is a bit behind in
drawing software, but not much.  Amiga 3D CAD on a professional level is
seriously lacking and support for the zillions of periferals is skimpy
in some areas, but the most needed ones are there.
  Costwise, there is no contest.  It is much cheaper overall to use an
Amiga for DTP and art.  The software prices far more than make up for the
hardware costs, and the friendliness and reliability of the Amiga OS can't
be beat.  Mac OS 8.5/8.6 is BUGGY, and the latest Mac G3 series has serious
hardware problems, especially with the buss and memory management.  Type 1,
type 2 and type 11 errors and resultant freezes and crashes occure typically
several times a day, and color management is a mixed-up mess where all of
your files are obsoleted and wont work right (from system 8.1 or earlier).
and guess what. They are doing it again with the change to system 9.
They keep changing the library and file formats in such a way that everything
gets screwed up.

  OK.  I got a little carryed away.  Sorry.  But my point is that the Amiga
is still a good useable platform, and we still have some advantages.  All
that is needed to cure most of the Amigas problems is upgrading for once
in a decade.  Shoot, on either Mac or wintel you are expected to upgrade
both hardware and software at least once a year and those who don't will find
some new piece of software they just bought for $500.00 not working untill
they buy several more expensive pieces of software and/or a new computer,
or at least makeing a hundred useless phone calls and installing a hundred
updates they found on various websites.  I am heavily emproiled at work in
a lengthy battle to get everything working on several Macs, and a co-worker
fights a continuing battle with windoze on many machines.

  windoze works well for some games and WP and internet, but get into serious
art and DTP and it's a continual headache.  The hardware is ALWAYS a
continual headache unless you find a combination that works and just stick
with it (including software).  Mac is crap at the moment if you are trying
to be up-to-date.

  My half-dead A4000 works all the time for me.  I never have trouble with it.
Even with 2 bad chips (no sound and no Zorro3) and a dying power pack I have
no trouble with it as long as I don't add more than one card (which overloads
the power pack).  Right now, my life is fighting with Macs all day, relaxing
with my Amigas at night.  If my Boxer doesn't come on time this time I am
going to repair and upgrade my A4000 with new CIA chips, new BusterR11, 300w
power pack, Phase 5 G4, and Graphics board (I have 2 of them but can't use
them due to the power pack problem).  At any rate it is getting Amiga OS3.5
and a new huge hard drive.  (the total of 9gb I have now isnt enough)  ;)


  Dang, did it again.  I'd better sign off before I think of something else
to say.

 @;u)>



cacha later,

Donovan Reeve (bubby.lnk@ispi.net)




