--BOUNDARY.1748653624.2

Hi Emil

On 25-Sep-99, Emil Oppeln Bronikowski wrote:

> how can i use custom fonts on bitmap? i can loadfont and use windowfont,
> but there is no bitmapfont command :)

Here is one way

Later...
-- 
God made the integers; all else is the work of Man.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/


--BOUNDARY.1748653624.2
Content-Disposition: attachment; filename="Bprint"

;---------------------------------------------------------------

;prints text to a bitmap using any standard intuifont
;including proportional and non-proportional
;can print in any colour and style
;can add dropshadows in any colour
;can automatically center the text

;original code by David McMinn
;effects added by Curt Esser
;last modified July 27, 1999 by Curt Esser

;***** IMPORTANT WARNING!!!!  ********************

; there is a bug in the function handling routines in some
; versions of acidlibs!!!!  If the style of the printing
; is messing up, uncomment the "Request" line in the
; function below to make sure the style you set is being
; passed correctly to the function!
; If it is not, get the acidlibs patch from Aminet/dev/basic
; to fix your acidlibs

;*************************************************

;NOTE: the example sends the bitmap to a window to be displayed,
;but you DO NOT NEED A WINDOW to use the routine...
;you can print on ANY currently used bitmap

;you MUST have a font loaded

;NOTE: needs amigalibs.res

;NOTE: if the text is too long to fit, it will wrap around
;and make a mess!

;the routine will use the Current Intuifont
;and the Current BitMap

;text$    = the string to print

;x        = the x position: if a negative value is given,
;           the text is centered horizontally on x,
;           if a positive value the text starts at x

;style    = the style of the printing - add them to get what you want
;           0 = normal
;           1 = bold
;           4 = italic
;           8 = extended
;  -  note that not all fonts allow all styles - sorry, but this is
;  -  a limitation of the font itself...

;y        = the y location to print the text

;textcol  = the colour for the text

;shadocol = the colour for the dropshadow
;           or use -1 for no dropshadow


Statement BPrint{text$,x.w,style.l,y.w,textcol.w,shadocol.w}

  enabl.l=79    ;the enable bits for setting the softstyle

  ;Request "","style="+Str$(style),"OK"

  DEFTYPE.RastPort rp

  InitRastPort_ &rp                        ;create a rastport
                                           ;for our bitmap
  rp\_BitMap = Addr BitMap(Used BitMap)

  SetFont_ &rp,Peek.l(Addr IntuiFont(Used IntuiFont)+8)

        ;this next bit works the same as the WJam command

  SetDrMd_ &rp,0                           ;print letters only
                                           ;no background rectangle

  styl.l=SetSoftStyle_ (&rp,style,enabl)   ;set text style


  If x<0                                   ;the centering routine
    x=Abs(x)
    pixels=TextLength_(&rp,&text$,Len(text$))
    x=x-pixels/2
    If x<1 Then x=1
  EndIf

  If shadocol=>0                           ;the dropshadow bit
    Move_ &rp,x+1,y+1                      ;locate the cursor
    SetAPen_ &rp,shadocol                  ;set the colour
    Text_ &rp,&text$,Len(text$)            ;print the shadow text
  EndIf
  Move_ &rp,x,y                            ;relocate the cursor
  SetAPen_ &rp,textcol                     ;set the colour
  Text_ &rp,&text$,Len(text$)              ;print foreground text

End Statement

;----------------------------------------------------------------

;demo

WBenchToFront_
FindScreen 0
LoadFont 0,"Diamond.font",12
Window 0,10,10,300,150,$1000,"Print Demo",1,0
BitMap 0,300,150,2
Cls 3
BPrint{"No shadow, Italic",10,4,15,2,-1}
BPrint{"Dropshadow & Centered!",-150,0,40,2,1}
BitMaptoWindow 0,0
MouseWait
End



--BOUNDARY.1748653624.2

