@NODE "Mail_739" "Re: Snap*!Shot!."
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Sun, 03 Oct 1999 06:45:59 -0500
Subject: Re: Snap*!Shot!.
X-UIDL: 644ab909d9efb4497630efdb43bdc527

Hi Vic

On 02-Oct-99, Vic E Babes wrote:
>> On 02-Oct-99, Thomas Cobb wrote:
>> 
>>> Once you've got your screen then use:
>>> 
>>> ScreensBitmap 0,0
>>> SaveBitmap 0,"File"
>>> 
>>> BUT! I'm not sure if this is a bug in Blitz or not, but sometimes it
>>> really messes up the picture. I think te problem is with interleaved
>>> screens - my workbench comes out twice as wide and with extra bits
>> down
>>> the side and bottom.
>> 
>> Yes! thats what happens to mine ;/ is there any way around it? :)
>> 
> 
> You could setup another bitmap, and then use blockscroll to scroll the
> bitmap you want, and then save that - that should cure the interleaved
> problem.  As to why you`ve got extra bits, that might be because its word
> aligning the bitmap.

Yes.

You can avoid this by using the SaveShape command instead.  But I think this
will only work if the width <=640 and height <=400  (at least on my system)

First Initialize a free shape the same size & depth you want to save
Now use ShapesBitMap to allow drawing to the shape
Then scroll the OS bitmap to the shape's bitmap
Now SaveShape this, with the palette of course.

Then Free the shape - no need to Free the bitmap, cuz there really isn't
one.

Now you will find your pic has no extra lines on it.

There is also the BDGFX.library on Aminet/dev/basic 
This has a "SaveILBM" command to fix this problem.

Later...
-- 
It could be worse - you could have an Atari ST.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/



