@NODE "Mail_744" "Re: Speed TEST"
 (envelope-from FlameDuck@software.dk)
Date: Mon, 18 Oct 1999 07:26:28 +0200
From: Mikkel =?iso-8859-1?Q?L=F8kke?= <FlameDuck@software.dk>
Subject: Re: Speed TEST
X-UIDL: 65e6104bc9b9c759b4a7ef557e36b6cd

At 19:35 16-10-99 +0100, you wrote:

>    Does someone, know the faster method for moving 30 shapes of 32*32 pixel
>max in a 256, or 128 cols screen with a background picture on a 030/50 Mhrz

>an example was very good

Well, if you're not too Xenophobic, there's allways Mildred, which can be
found at http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk  and there are also quite alot
of really good examples.

If you are Xenophobic on the other hand I would divide the blits into
either 2*16 blits on different frames or 4*8 blits each fourth frame.
Offcouse assuming this is a game, and the main loop runs in under 1
frame... If you're using more CPU time than that spreading out the blits
might not be a good idea, it depends on what type of game it is...

Oh, and the fastest way to copy them is either using Blit or the external
CPU blit routines, the CPU blit routines can be found on allmost any good
Blitz site.

Note, for 28Mhz 68020 and above, blitting with the CPU is faster than the
blitter...


/FlameDuck/



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_745" "Re: Speed TEST"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Mon, 18 Oct 1999 18:53:21 +0100
