@NODE "Mail_784" "Re: Two questions"
 id 11fhiS-0007Gy-00; Mon, 25 Oct 1999 11:51:04 +0100
Sender: tdc98@doc.ic.ac.uk
Date: Mon, 25 Oct 1999 11:51:04 +0100
From: Thomas Cobb <tdc98@doc.ic.ac.uk>
X-Accept-Language: en
Subject: Re: Two questions
Encoding: 7bit
X-UIDL: 1ed8f4d5346c4c477474c66d9f9c145d

Tony Rolfe wrote:

> Hi,
>
> If anyone can help, I'd be really happy
>
> 1.  I have a screen, with a borderless backdrop window, with some
> GTString Gadgets.    One of the gadgets is active and has a cursor in
> it.    If I click the screen-shuffle gadget the screen goes away and
> if I keep clicking on each screen in turn, mine comes back.  However,
> the gadget is no longer active and has no cursor.   Is there a way to
> recognise that my screen has just arrived at the front and activate a
> gadget?  (Doesn't matter if it was the same one).

MultiCX has an option to remember (and then reactivate) the active
window of a flipped screen (something like this should be part of the os
- it's very annoying to switch between two screens and find when you
type something it goes to the last screen).
If you want to do it yourself, how about comparing the front screen
address with your screen address at suitable times (every vwait 5 or
every screenflip) and if they are the same reactivate your window and
gadget.

    Thom



